<div id='content'>
<h1>sns_page_hook</h1>
<div class='screenshot'>
<a href="/system/screenshots/232/large/Radiant_CMS_-_.jpg?1277827222"><img alt="Radiant_cms_-_" src="/system/screenshots/232/medium/Radiant_CMS_-_.jpg?1277827222" /></a>
</div>
<div style='width: 75%'>
<div class='big'>
<p>Ever wanted to upload images and files with Radiant? Cool, there are some extensions around here for that.</p>
<p>What about managing stylesheets and javascripts from the Radiant interface? Yeah there&#8217;s one for that too.</p>
<p>But what about&#8230; wait for it&#8230; using Page tags within your stylesheets? Well with this extension you can do that. Read about it at the <a href="http://www.saturnflyer.com/blog/jim/2010/06/29/ruby-metaprogramming-is-awesome/">Saturn Flyer Blog.</a></p>
<p>Need a stylesheet that uses a url from a page attachment? Then make one. You can easily add <code>#something { background: url('&lt;r:find url="/my/url"&gt;&lt;r:attachments:url name="somefile.gif" /&gt;&lt;/r:find&gt;') }</code> and it works. That&#8217;s right, without this extension, <span class="caps">SNS</span> isn&#8217;t able to use your regular page tags; but now it can.</p>
<p>Righteous, dude.</p>
<p>There may be some things that don&#8217;t work since the tags added to the Page model expect there to be pages and when we add them to the TextAsset model from the <span class="caps">SNS</span> extension, some problem may</p>
</div>
